</table>
<p><b>Howard Phillips Lovecraft</b> (August 20, 1890 – March 15, 1937) was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a> of <a href="/wiki/Horror_fiction" title="Horror fiction">horror</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fantasy_fiction" title="Fantasy fiction" class="mw-redirect">fantasy</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a>, known then simply as <a href="/wiki/Weird_fiction" title="Weird fiction">weird fiction</a>.</p>
<p>Lovecraft's major inspiration and invention was <a href="/wiki/Cosmicism" title="Cosmicism">cosmic</a> horror; the idea that life is incomprehensible to human minds and that the universe is fundamentally alien. Those who genuinely reason, like his protagonists, gamble with sanity. Lovecraft has developed a cult following for his <a href="/wiki/Cthulhu_Mythos" title="Cthulhu Mythos">Cthulhu Mythos</a>, a series of loosely interconnected fiction featuring a <a href="/wiki/Pantheon_(gods)" title="Pantheon (gods)">pantheon</a> of human-nullifying entities, as well as the <a href="/wiki/Necronomicon" title="Necronomicon">Necronomicon</a>, a fictional <a href="/wiki/Grimoire" title="Grimoire">grimoire</a> of magical rites and forbidden lore. His works were deeply pessimistic and cynical, challenging the values of the <a href="/wiki/Age_of_Enlightenment" title="Age of Enlightenment">Enlightenment</a>, <a href="/wiki/Romanticism" title="Romanticism">Romanticism</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Christian_humanism" title="Christian humanism">Christian humanism</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Lovecraft's protagonists usually achieve the mirror-opposite of traditional <a href="/wiki/Gnosis" title="Gnosis">gnosis</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mysticism" title="Mysticism">mysticism</a> by momentarily glimpsing the horror of <a href="/wiki/Ultimate_reality" title="Ultimate reality" class="mw-redirect">ultimate reality</a>.</p>
<p>Although Lovecraft's readership was limited during his life, his reputation has grown over the decades, and he is now commonly regarded as one of the most influential horror writers of the 20th century, who together with <a href="/wiki/Edgar_Allan_Poe" title="Edgar Allan Poe">Edgar Allan Poe</a> has exerted "an incalculable influence on succeeding generations of writers of horror fiction".<sup id="cite_ref-Oates_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oates-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Stephen_King" title="Stephen King">Stephen King</a> has called Lovecraft "the twentieth Century's greatest practitioner of the classic horror tale."<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
